==Old English==
===Etymology===
Representing the Indo-European demonstrative pronouns ''*te-, *to-'', adapted in West Germanic languages as definite articles.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[the|thē]], [[thiu]], [[that]] (Dutch [[de]]), Old High German [[ther]], [[thiu]], [[thaz]] (German [[der]], [[die]], [[das]]), Old Norse [[ðat]] ''n'', Gothic [[𐌸𐌰𐍄𐌰]] ''n'', Greek [[το]] ''n'', Lithuanian [[tas|tàs]] ''m'', [[ta|tà]] ''f'', Slavic ''*tъ, *ta, *to'' (Russian [[тот]], [[та]], [[то]]).  See also ''s-'' stem variants represented by Old English [[se#Old English|se]], [[seo|sēo]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ðæt/

===Demonstrative Pronoun===
'''þæt''' ''n''
# definite article: [[the]]
#:''þæt scip'': the ship
# demonstrative adjective: [[that]], [[those]]
#:''þæt gewrit wrat Widsið'': Widsith wrote that letter
# pronoun: [[it]], [[they]]
#:''æfter þam...'': after that...

===Declension===
*Nominative: '''þæt''' (''plural'' '''þā''')
*Accusative: '''þæt''' (''plural '''þā''')
*Genitive: '''þæs''' (''plural'' '''þāra''', '''þǣra''')
*Dative: '''þǣm''', '''þām''' (''plural'' '''þǣm''', '''þām''')
*Instrumental: '''þȳ''', '''þī''', '''þōn'''

===See also===
